  "why": "The paper's fuzzing setup enforces semantic-consistency / naturalness checks on each mutation step (via an is_valid() check with per-mutation pixel-change thresholds, and they evaluate naturalness using IS/FID and report that NLC-guided mutations produce more natural inputs). However, the validity check and acceptance condition are applied between the newly mutated input and the currently selected seed/mutant (is_valid(sˆ, s) in Alg.1), i.e., similarity is controlled relative to the previous mutated input rather than anchored to the original seed. The design therefore enforces plausibility between successive mutation steps but does not introduce an explicit mechanism to constrain cumulative drift relative to the original seed across many iterations. This matches the metric definition of Medium: controls similarity/naturalness step-by-step but does not account for cumulative distortion across iterations.",
